plausible_answers.text: the monarch of Norway the right to withhold royal assent from any bill passed by the Storting

context: <a0_0>Articles <b5_0><b6_0>77–79<b6_0/><b5_0/><a0_0/> of the Norwegian Constitution specifically grant <b3_0>the monarch of Norway the right to withhold royal assent from any bill passed by the Storting<b3_0/>. Should the sovereign ever choose to exercise this privilege, <a1_0>Article <b4_0>79<b4_0/><a1_0/> provides a means by which his veto may be over-ridden: "If a Bill has been passed unaltered by two sessions of the Storting, constituted after <a2_0>two<a2_0/> separate successive elections and separated from each other by at least two intervening sessions of the Storting, without a divergent Bill having been passed by any Storting in the period between the first and last adoption, and it is then submitted to the King with a petition that His Majesty shall not refuse his assent to a Bill which, after the most mature deliberation, the Storting considers to be beneficial, it shall become law even if the Royal Assent is not accorded before the Storting goes into recess."
